Revision Plan

Core recommendation

The draft should move from "EU repairability scoring has a credibility problem" to a more constructive, enforcement-centered frame:

The EU is leading the world on repair policy, but the rules are only as strong as the evidence, enforcement, and public access behind them.

That frame preserves the news value while reducing the risk of sounding like we are attacking the EU project itself. The story is not "EU scores suck." The story is that Europe has created the world's most ambitious repair transparency infrastructure, and our investigation found that manufacturers and retailers are already finding weak points in that system: self-declared scores that are hard to verify, missing or useless repair links, missing labels at retail, and professional repairers still blocked from information they should be able to access.

This is a stronger political frame because it asks EU institutions to finish the job, not to abandon or discredit the work they have started. It also gives reporters a clear headline:

Europe's repair rules are here. Our investigation found the enforcement gaps.

Why the current draft triggers EU-bashing concerns

The current headline is the main problem: "EU repairability scoring has a credibility problem." It puts "EU" and "credibility problem" in the same sentence before the reader understands what kind of scores are involved, which rules are French versus EU-wide, what is self-reported, and what has or has not taken effect yet. That makes the institutional target feel like the EU, not the manufacturers, retailers, and enforcement gaps.

The dek compounds this: "France and the EU have started putting those answers on labels and public product records. Our findings show that the public data is spotty, misleading, and in some cases even maybe flat-out wrong." This is punchy, but it collapses several regimes into one "public data" bucket. Ugo's concern is right: the story currently bundles the French Repairability Index, the EU smartphone/tablet energy label and EPREL records, retailer display obligations, dryer parts-price requirements, and professional-repairer information access. Those pieces can belong in the same investigation, but the frame has to explain why they belong together.

The draft's section labels reinforce the problem. "Repairability Data Problem 1/2/3/4/5" makes all findings sound like failures of "repairability data," even when the issue is retailer non-display, market surveillance, parts-price link compliance, or repair information access. That narrows the frame too much and makes the disparate pieces feel forced.

The ASUS module is also too accusatory in its current presentation. "ASUS gave themselves 10/10. Our repairability engineers disagree" is a useful hook, but the copy compares the French score and the iFixit score too directly. Thomas is right that the iFixit score is not a one-to-one alternative to the French Repairability Index. The stronger claim is narrower: our teardown and scoring found concrete repair barriers that should make a perfect repairability claim require much more transparent evidence.

The "more than 40 laptops" line should be dropped or heavily qualified. Manuel and Thomas are right that the broader count appears to include many variants/configurations of a few model families. If we keep the point as currently phrased, it can imply ASUS is making perfect claims across a huge independent range of products, which is misleading. Use one tested product and, if needed, a parenthetical that public datasets contain multiple 10/10 ASUS variants, but ASUS's dedicated repairability site appears to highlight two 10/10 model lines.

The Jacob/professional repairer story needs a timing caveat. The draft currently says "EU rules do not only require a label" and "the findings show that access still breaks down." That is true for existing ecodesign repair-information obligations, but Ugo is right that the broader Right to Repair Directive is not yet fully applicable. The European Commission states that Directive (EU) 2024/1799 was adopted on June 13, 2024, entered into force on July 30, 2024, and must be transposed and applied from July 31, 2026. So the draft should not say or imply that the Right to Repair Directive has already failed. It should say: existing ecodesign access rules are still unevenly enforced, and the incoming Right to Repair Directive will only work if those enforcement gaps are fixed.

What to preserve

The evidence is strong. The frame is the weak point, not the reporting. Keep:

- The 81% smartphone/tablet information-sheet finding: 1,670 of 2,054 active records did not lead to usable spare-parts price information.
- The 55% dryer finding: 2,832 of 5,159 active dryer records did not lead to required spare-parts price information.
- The missing retail label checks: mediamarkt.de, saturn.de, MediaMarkt Belgium online, Amazon.de examples, and Brussels physical-store checks.
- The Temu/AliExpress finding, especially as a vivid example of EPREL accepting legally relevant links that do not function as a genuine repair channel.
- The ASUS Flow Z13 case, but as a transparency and verification case study, not as a direct "iFixit proves French score wrong" comparison.
- The Jacob story, but positioned as "existing repair-information rights still break down in practice" and "a warning sign for the incoming right-to-repair implementation."

Best broad narrative

Suggested nut graf:

"Europe is doing what the rest of the world has not: putting repairability, spare-parts access, and repair information into consumer-facing law. That is the right direction. But an iFixit review of public repair datasets, retailer listings, product information sheets, and a real repairer's attempt to obtain service information found a recurring problem: the rules often depend on self-reporting, unverified links, and weak market surveillance. The result is a repair system that looks strong on paper but can still fail consumers and independent repairers at the moment they need it."

This gives reporters:

- A clear protagonist: the EU as repair-policy leader.
- A clear problem: enforcement and verification gaps.
- A clear antagonist: manufacturers/retailers exploiting or neglecting weak points.
- A clear policy takeaway: keep going, audit the data, enforce the rules, close loopholes.

Ten alternate framing approaches

1. "Europe's repair rules are a breakthrough. Now comes the hard part."

Gain: Very low EU-bashing risk. It flatters the ambition while making enforcement the news. It also creates a natural before/after structure: rules passed, implementation tested, gaps found.

Loss: Less immediately scandalous than "credibility problem." It may need a sharper dek to make the findings feel urgent.

Better: Politically safest and accurate across all pieces of the investigation.

Worse: "Hard part" is broad and slightly familiar.

2. "Repair labels are only as good as the data behind them."

Gain: Clear, memorable, and broadly applicable to French scores, EPREL records, parts-price links, and retailer display.

Loss: Still centers labels/data, so Jacob's professional-access story feels like an add-on unless the piece explicitly says labels are one part of a wider repair-information system.

Better: Strong consumer-facing clarity.

Worse: Less policy-forward and less urgent.

3. "Europe is leading on repair. Manufacturers are testing the limits."

Gain: Keeps the EU positive and shifts accountability toward companies. This is probably the punchiest constructive frame.

Loss: It requires careful legal language because not every example proves deliberate testing or bad faith. Some failures may be negligence, bad data entry, platform confusion, or market-surveillance gaps.

Better: Newsier and more memorable than Thomas's proposed frame.

Worse: "Testing the limits" can imply intent that we cannot prove in every case.

4. "The repair revolution has a paperwork problem."

Gain: Punchy, approachable, and reporter-friendly. It captures the absurdity of missing links, empty fields, score records, retail labels, and access forms.

Loss: "Paperwork" may undersell the stakes: consumers cannot compare products, repairers cannot fix devices, and manufacturers can claim high scores without public verification.

Better: Very headlineable.

Worse: Too cute for the seriousness of enforcement failures.

5. "A repair score is not a repair right."

Gain: Strong and memorable. It allows the piece to move beyond scoring into parts prices, labels, and professional information access.

Loss: Could be read as dismissive of repair scores unless the deck clearly says scores are useful but insufficient.

Better: Excellent bridge from scoring to the wider right-to-repair system.

Worse: Less specific to Europe unless the headline/dek supplies that.

6. "Europe gave repair a label. Manufacturers still control the fine print."

Gain: Strong consumer hook and clear power dynamic. Works well with self-reporting, hidden evidence, and hard-to-find parts prices.

Loss: "Manufacturers still control" may overstate the case for retailer failures and marketplace importers.

Better: Good for an iFixit voice.

Worse: Slightly adversarial and might still make EU advocates worry if not paired with pro-EU context.

7. "The EU's repair promise needs an enforcement engine."

Gain: Directly matches Ugo's and Thomas's concerns. It names the solution.

Loss: "Enforcement engine" is less natural language and less headline-friendly.

Better: Strong for policy readers.

Worse: Less vivid for general reporters.

8. "Repair transparency is becoming law. Our check found the blind spots."

Gain: Accurate across all findings. "Blind spots" is less hostile than "failure" or "credibility problem."

Loss: "Our check" sounds smaller than the research deserves unless paired with the dataset numbers.

Better: Balanced and easy to defend.

Worse: Not as punchy.

9. "Europe's repair labels can work, but only if someone checks the receipts."

Gain: Memorable and enforcement-centered. "Checks the receipts" maps well to self-declared scores, missing links, and retailer display obligations.

Loss: Informal phrasing might be too idiomatic for an international policy story.

Better: Good iFixit/blog voice.

Worse: Could sound less serious in a formal report.

10. "The next repair fight is not passing rules. It is making them real."

Gain: Broad enough for all pieces, politically constructive, and forward-looking. It avoids implying the rules are inherently flawed.

Loss: It is more essay-like than investigative. Needs hard numbers in the dek.

Better: Best for a campaign narrative.

Worse: Less specific to the findings unless the subhead lands hard.

Top three frames

Top frame 1: "Europe is leading on repair. Manufacturers are testing the limits."

Why it is best: It is the strongest balance of punch and political safety. It makes the EU the leader, not the villain. It also gives reporters a clear conflict: rules versus manufacturers' implementation choices. This framing can carry all the evidence if the dek explicitly includes retailers and enforcement.

Headline/dek options:

1. Europe Is Leading on Repair. Manufacturers Are Testing the Limits.
Dek: An iFixit review found missing repair labels, empty parts-price links, marketplace listings in official records, and a 10/10 ASUS claim that deserves public proof.

2. The EU Built the World's Strongest Repair Rules. Companies Are Finding the Weak Spots.
Dek: From missing smartphone labels to repair links that point to Temu, our review shows why Europe's repair reforms need audits, enforcement, and public evidence behind every score.

3. Europe's Repair Rules Are Here. The Loopholes Are Already Showing.
Dek: Public repair records and retailer checks reveal missing labels, unusable parts-price links, and self-declared scores that consumers cannot meaningfully verify.

Top frame 2: "A repair score is not a repair right."

Why it is best: It elegantly solves the "disparate pieces" problem. The story is not only about repairability scoring; it is about the gap between a label/score and the practical conditions needed to repair: parts, prices, manuals, retailer display, professional access, and enforcement. It is also short enough for reporters to remember.

Headline/dek options:

1. A Repair Score Is Not a Repair Right.
Dek: Europe has moved faster than anyone to make repair visible to consumers. Our investigation found the next challenge: making those scores, links, labels, and information rights work in practice.

2. Europe Has Repair Scores. Consumers Still Need Repair Proof.
Dek: We found empty public records, missing retailer labels, marketplace "repair" links, and a perfect ASUS score that independent teardown evidence does not support.

3. The Label Says Repairable. The Fine Print Tells Another Story.
Dek: EU and French repair systems are a major step forward, but our review found weak verification, missing parts-price information, and repairers still fighting for access.

Top frame 3: "Europe's repair rules are a breakthrough. Now comes the hard part."

Why it is best: This is the safest advocacy frame. It directly addresses Ugo's first concern because it starts from support for EU institutions and research groups. It also lets iFixit be critical without sounding nihilistic: the rules make sense, but enforcement, evidence, and redress need to catch up.

Headline/dek options:

1. Europe's Repair Rules Are a Breakthrough. Now Comes the Hard Part.
Dek: iFixit found missing labels, broken repair links, unverifiable high scores, and blocked repair information - evidence that ambitious repair laws need serious enforcement to deliver.

2. The EU Is Raising the Bar on Repair. Our Data Shows Where It Still Falls Short.
Dek: From smartphone labels to dryer parts prices and professional repair access, Europe's repair reforms are promising but still too easy to ignore.

3. Europe Is Winning the Repair Policy Race. It Can't Stop at the Starting Line.
Dek: New repair labels and information requirements are a global model, but our review found manufacturers and retailers leaving consumers without the proof and access the rules are meant to provide.

Recommended headline direction

Use either:

"Europe Is Leading on Repair. Manufacturers Are Testing the Limits."

or:

"A Repair Score Is Not a Repair Right."

The first is the best news headline. The second is the best conceptual headline. If the goal is reporter pickup, use the first and make the dek factual and number-driven.

Suggested revised hero

Eyebrow: Investigation

Headline: Europe Is Leading on Repair. Manufacturers Are Testing the Limits.

Dek: The EU and France have created some of the world's strongest repair labels and information rules. An iFixit review found missing retailer labels, empty parts-price records, marketplace links in official repair fields, and a 10/10 ASUS repairability claim that needs public evidence.

Key metrics:

- 81% of active smartphone/tablet information sheets we reviewed did not lead to required spare-parts price information.
- 55% of active dryer information sheets we reviewed did not lead to required spare-parts price information.
- 57% of mediamarkt.de smartphone listings and 56% of saturn.de smartphone listings lacked a score in our checks.
- ASUS publicly claims a 10/10 French repairability score for the ROG Flow Z13 GZ302EA; our teardown found meaningful barriers that should make any perfect score transparent and auditable.

More careful ASUS approach

Do not frame the ASUS case as "French score versus iFixit score, therefore French score is wrong." Ugo is right that the scoring systems are not comparable. The French Repairability Index and iFixit's score use different criteria, weights, categories, and evidence standards.

Use this structure instead:

1. State the official claim precisely.

"ASUS's dedicated French repairability site claims a 10/10 score for the ROG Flow Z13 GZ302EA. Public datasets also contain multiple 10/10 ASUS model variants, but those appear to be variants/configurations of a small number of model families, not dozens of unrelated product designs."

2. Acknowledge the product's real strengths.

"The Flow Z13 is not a repairability disaster. By modern tablet/laptop standards, it does several things well: the display can be removed with little or no adhesive, the battery is screwed down rather than glued, the SSD is accessible behind a hatch, cameras and several modules are replaceable, and ASUS publishes a useful service manual."

3. Explain what we found that makes "perfect" hard to accept without evidence.

"Our teardown also found barriers that are difficult to square with an unqualified perfect score: soldered RAM, soldered wireless, soldered ports, one fan trapped under the heatsink, liquid metal making heatsink removal riskier, incomplete service documentation, weak parts discoverability, and official support paths that may require diagnostics or serial-number-dependent workflows."

4. Avoid direct score equivalence.

Use:

"Our independent iFixit score is not a replacement French Repairability Index score. It is a separate assessment. But the process of scoring the device gave us physical evidence that any 10/10 claim should be backed by public, criterion-by-criterion documentation."

Avoid:

"ASUS says 10/10; iFixit says 7.4/10; therefore ASUS is wrong."

5. Focus on transparency and verifiability.

"The policy issue is not that iFixit's score and the French score differ. The policy issue is that consumers cannot easily audit how ASUS assigned full marks for the relevant French criteria, and some parts of the French score necessarily depend on commitments or evidence that a member of the public cannot verify by examining the product."

6. Incorporate Thomas's distinction on non-public data.

"Some French score elements cannot be audited from a teardown alone. For example, a manufacturer's commitment to provide spare parts for a certain duration may require contracts, supply records, or historical fulfillment evidence. Other elements are not necessarily non-public in principle but are not exposed in a consumer-verifiable way, such as detailed step counts for disassembly or the exact basis for a sub-score."

7. Suggest the remedy.

"Perfect self-scores should come with public scorecards, source evidence, and a redress mechanism if the promised parts, documents, or support periods are not delivered later."

Replacement ASUS section language

Current: "ASUS gave themselves 10/10. Our repairability engineers disagree."

Better: "ASUS says this repairable device is perfect. The evidence should be public."

Current: "The central contradiction: ASUS declares a perfect French score, while independent scoring finds real repair barriers..."

Better: "The central issue is not that two scoring systems produce different numbers. It is that a perfect self-declared score should be verifiable, especially when a teardown reveals meaningful repair barriers."

Current: "Independent iFixit scoring treats the device as a tablet... Even then, the result is 7.4/10, not 10/10."

Better: "iFixit scored the Flow Z13 under our tablet methodology because the main components sit behind the display and the keyboard detaches. That score is not directly comparable to the French laptop score, but the teardown behind it is still evidence: this is a relatively repairable device with real limitations, not an obviously perfect one."

Data change on ASUS 10/10 counts

Remove:

"ASUS reports perfect 10/10 French Repairability Index scores for more than 40 laptops..."

Replace with:

"ASUS's dedicated French repairability site claims 10/10 scores for the ROG Flow Z13 GZ302EA and the ROG Zephyrus GU605MZ. A broader public dataset contains many 10/10 ASUS entries, but those appear to be variants of a small number of model families, so the count should not be used as evidence of a massive pattern across unrelated designs."

If the count is kept anywhere, use:

"Multiple ASUS model variants in public data are listed at 10/10, concentrated in the Strix G16, Strix G18, and Flow Z13 families."

Do not use:

"More than 40 ASUS laptops" or "more than 50 ASUS laptops" as a standalone claim.

